    <title>Combined summary - Small Nodes: A Better Alternative to Pruned Nodes</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T00:25:02.876538+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-April/014187.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is actively searching for ways to increase the number of full nodes on its network. One proposal suggests adding a third mode for nodes, allowing them to signal "I keep the last 1000 blocks." Another proposal suggests a "random pruning mode" for nodes, which stores a random set of blocks and drops random blocks as the node runs out of disk space. However, this proposal has significant disadvantages due to the probability of not being able to download a given block, especially with active adversaries.A new proposal has been made to create an alternative to pruned nodes that would be non-risky to ship as a default in bitcoin-core. This proposal suggests the creation of 'small nodes' which will only need to store around 20% of the blockchain, reducing disk consumption from over 100GB to less than 30 GB. Small nodes will pick an index between 5-256 and Reed-Solomon coding will be used to erasure code the block using a 5-of-256 scheme, with the node picking the piece that corresponds to its index and storing that instead. When paired with any 5 unique fragments, the full block can be recovered. Nodes can optionally store more than one fragment each. The high barrier of entry due to bandwidth requirements makes it difficult for people living in third world countries without adequate data packages from ISPs to set up a full node. There is no financial incentive for running a node, making it a sunk cost and only an ideological one. However, it is important to allow participation in the network for those who cannot afford to run a node, such as by supporting proposals or writing applications on top of Bitcoin. Financially incentivizing nodes is a complex issue, as it could allow malicious actors to automate deployment, but offering rewards for long-term commitment could be a potential solution. Furthermore, the proposal requires a non-trivial amount of code to implement.Several proposals have been made on the Bitcoin-dev mailing list to address the high barrier to entry for running full nodes due to bandwidth and disk space requirements. One proposal suggests using pruned nodes that can partially serve historical blocks, while another proposal suggests compactly indicating which blocks a node has. David Vorick proposes an alternative to pruned nodes called "small nodes", which would require less than 30GB of disk space and store only 20% of the blockchain using Reed-Solomon coding. The Bitcoin network has been facing high failure probabilities due to an active attacker targeting less commonly available blocks. To address this issue, nodes could store a random percentage of these blocks along with their deterministic random set and a patch/fill set to deter attacks. However, there are limitations to this proposal such as Sybil attacks and proof of independent storage. A rewarding system that incentivizes those with resources to run full nodes was suggested in the discussion on the mailing list.There have been various proposals made to reduce the amount of storage required to run a full node on the Bitcoin network. One idea is to use Forward Error Correction (FEC) to break up the blockchain data into smaller parts and allow smaller subsets of data to be stored while still being able to reconstruct the entire chain if needed. Another suggestion is to use Reed-Solomon (RS) codes to encode Bitcoin blocks and divide them into 255 fragments. Overall, there have been numerous discussions and proposals regarding reducing storage requirements and increasing the number of full nodes on the Bitcoin network. The goal is to improve the reliability and health of the overall network while addressing the various challenges and limitations faced by users.</summary>
